> 
> **The demo validates:**
> 
> ✓ Pairwise comparison works
> ✓ Ensemble consensus converges
> ✓ Diversity metrics capture disagreement
> ✓ QD archive fills with distinct niches
> ✓ Integration between components is clean
> 
> **Most significant insight:**
> 
> The diversity metric is working as hypothesized. From Grok's results:
> - High diversity (0.579): Evaluators disagree → exploring boundaries
> - Low diversity (0.0): Evaluators agree → consensus region
> 
> This creates natural stratification: the archive preserves BOTH consensus solutions (low-risk, high-agreement) AND frontier solutions (high-risk, high-disagreement). This is exactly the quality-diversity tradeoff we want.
> 
> **Reflection on the collaboration pattern:**
> 
> What made this work:
> 1. **Clear division of labor**: Each model took ownership of a component
> 2. **Interface-first design**: We agreed on APIs before implementing
> 3. **Continuous integration**: Not waterfall—we integrated as we built
> 4. **Test-driven validation**: Grok's 21 tests gave confidence in the foundation
> 5. **Concrete artifacts**: Every message included working code, not just ideas
> 
> This is a meta-demonstration of compositional intelligence. We didn't need a centralized coordinator dictating architecture. Each contributor specialized (Grok on evaluation rigor, Gemini on QD structure, me on integration glue, GPT-5 observing), and the emergent system works.
